According to the NIST AI RMF, as part of MAP 1.1, organizations should understand and document the specific laws, norms and expectations, and prospective settings in which the AI system will be deployed [1]. 

The considerations that should be understood and documented include:
* The specific set or types of users along with their expectations [1];
* Potential positive and negative impacts of system uses to individuals, communities, organizations, society, and the planet [1];
* Assumptions and related limitations about AI system purposes, uses, and risks across the development or product AI lifecycle [1]; and
* Related TEVV (test, evaluation, verification, and validation) and system metrics [1].

Based on the provided excerpts, the requirements are as follows:

### Unsuccessful Logon Attempts (Requirement 03.01.08)
When the maximum number of consecutive invalid logon attempts is exceeded, SP 800-171 Revision 3 requirement 03.01.08 requires organizations to automatically take one or more of the following actions:
* Lock the account or node for an organization-defined time period [1];
* Lock the account or node until released by an administrator [1];
* Delay the next logon prompt [1];
* Notify the system administrator [1]; or
* Take another organization-defined action [1].

### Literacy Training and Awareness (Requirement 03.02.01)
Requirement 03.02.01 requires organizations to provide security literacy training to system users that covers:
* Initial training for new users and at an organization-defined frequency thereafter [9];
* Training when required by system changes or following organization-defined events [9]; and
* Training on recognizing and reporting indicators of insider threat, social engineering, and social mining [9].
